WEBVTT

00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:03.060
Yeah, like, like, again, because I'm running a small team, my

00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:06.340
opportunity cost of someone failing, not because of them,

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:10.860
but the data is actually high. So I don't have a like a

00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:13.500
bulletproof way to sort of prioritize projects. I mean,

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:17.520
generally speaking, we try to look at revenue potential, is

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:21.980
the data completely new? Or is it something that is new? And is

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:24.580
it new and can be linked to something we already have?

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:27.860
Generally, if you get something that's sort of independent from

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:30.719
the rest of the database, you're likely your value proposition is

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:35.480
going to be much harder. But if it's something that is related

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:37.840
to some of the companies we cover today, and they have other

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:44.599
measures, then there's a higher success chances. But yeah, it's

00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:46.919
happened to me where you basically work on something for

00:00:46.919 --> 00:00:50.279
like, six months plus, and then you end up with like, well, I

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:57.680
guess it didn't work. It's unfortunate, but I mean, it

00:00:57.680 --> 00:00:59.900
kind of comes back to the business side, because you kind

00:00:59.900 --> 00:01:05.059
of try to whoever's adding this project, you try to do your best

00:01:05.059 --> 00:01:11.260
to have them explain in very simple terms, what they want out

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:16.019
of it. Right. And that's where I kind of use that sometimes when

00:01:16.019 --> 00:01:18.660
things kind of fall apart, they're not very well defined.

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:22.620
And it's like, well, we really didn't know. So we tried and it

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:25.620
took a while because of these complexities. And at least we

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:29.440
found out that why we failed. So that's not really an

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:32.339
opportunity anymore. So that way, you kind of dance a bit

00:01:32.339 --> 00:01:36.080
around the issue, right?

